# @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant E (2 stories), default intro, teaching: visual hierarchy

@text
Before the first word is read, the eye has already made a decision.
It moves across the page in under a second, looking for structure.
What it finds in that moment changes how far the reader gets.

@text
In eye-tracking studies, researchers watched readers scan printed pages with identical content but different layouts.
Pages with one large block of text were abandoned almost twice as often as pages broken into sections.
The readers had not read a single word when the decision formed.
Their eyes swept across the wall of text for less than a second and moved on.
The eye was mapping the terrain before the brain started reading.

@text
The same effect appears in digital reading.
A long article with no headings, no breaks, and no images loses roughly half its readers before the third paragraph.
The same article, reformatted with section breaks and a clear visual structure, holds them nearly twice as long.
The words do not change, but the structure does, and so does the number of readers who stay.

@question
What were the eye-tracking studies showing about abandoned pages?

answer: Readers gave up because the content was too difficult.
consequence: The content was identical across all pages. Only the layout changed.

answer: The eye decided whether to continue before any reading had started.
consequence: The eye mapped the layout in under a second, and that map predicted how far readers got.

answer: Short paragraphs caused readers to skip over important information.
consequence: Shorter paragraphs kept readers longer. The eye reads structure as a sign of what the reading will cost.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The layout signals to the eye whether the page is worth the effort. That signal arrives before the first sentence is read.
hint: Notice that the content was identical in every version of the page.

@pause
A newspaper column is narrow because the eye can follow a short line without moving the head.

@text
<c:g>Visual hierarchy</c:g> is the arrangement of headings, text, and white space on a page so the eye knows where to start and what comes next.
It is the first of the layout choices that decide how far a reader gets, arriving before a single word has been read.
A heading, a paragraph break, or a wider margin all speak to the eye before the brain reads a word.
A page with no hierarchy asks the eye to do the designer's job.
Most eyes refuse.

@true_false
A reader who finds a page visually confusing will slow down and read more carefully.

true: True, difficulty makes readers pay closer attention.
consequence: Difficulty signals effort, and most readers respond to effort by stopping rather than by slowing down.

false: False, visual confusion is more likely to make a reader stop.
consequence: The eye reads layout as a signal of how hard the reading will be. Confusion becomes an exit.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The eye uses layout as a shortcut for the effort the reading will require. A confusing page signals a hard read, and most readers find the next page instead.
hint: Notice what happens in the body when a page immediately feels wrong to open.

@reflect
A book abandoned after one glance: a dense academic paper or a cluttered website.
A page that felt easy before the first sentence: wide margins, short paragraphs, or clear headings.
A layout choice that would have kept a reader going: a subheading or a shorter paragraph.

@text
The eye makes its decision before the mind does, and no amount of good writing overcomes a layout the eye has already refused.
The next question is what happens once the reader actually opens the book and looks at the first page.

@package
What the Eye Decides First...
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant B (2 stories), misconception intro, teaching: affordance

@text
Most readers and writers believe the cover is <c:r>what decides whether a book gets finished</c:r>.
The cover is what gets the book picked off the shelf.
After that, so the thinking goes, the writing takes over.

@text
A woman picks up a book she has been meaning to read for a year.
The cover is exactly what caught her attention in the shop.
She opens it to the first page.
The text is set in a small font, packed tightly, with no paragraph breaks for the first three pages.
She reads the first sentence, then the second.
By the fifth line she puts the book down and does not return to it.

@text
A different book sits on the same shelf.
The cover is forgettable, and she almost passes it.
She opens it anyway.
The first page has a short opening paragraph, generous margins, and a type size that does not strain the eye.
She reads the whole page without noticing she is reading.
By the second page, the cover has stopped mattering entirely.
She buys the book.

@question
Why did she put down the first book and buy the second?

answer: The writing quality. Better prose made the second book easier to read.
consequence: The stories focus on layout. The sentences themselves stayed the same in both books.

answer: The way the first page was designed told her how much the reading would cost.
consequence: The first page told her the cost before the writing had a chance. One invited her in, the other pushed her out.

answer: Her mood. She was more patient by the time she reached the second book.
consequence: The same reader opened both books on the same afternoon. The first page was where the difference lived.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The first page does the real work of keeping the reader, long before the writing itself has a chance to matter.
hint: Think about what the reader's body was doing before her mind made the decision.

@text
<c:g>Affordance</c:g> is the signal an object sends about how it wants to be used.
In a book, the first interior page is the strongest affordance signal a reader encounters after the cover.
The tight, dense page told her the reading would cost effort before she had read a sentence.
The clear, open page invited her in without a single word about the content.
The layout carried the message, while the prose waited its turn.
A cover gets the book opened, and the affordance of the first page decides whether it stays open.

@true_false
A well-designed cover is enough to keep a reader engaged once the book is open.

true: True, a strong cover creates an expectation that carries the reader forward.
consequence: Expectation fades quickly. Once the book is open, the layout takes over.

false: False, the cover's work ends when the reader opens the book.
consequence: The affordance of the interior pages decides whether the reader stays. The cover is the invitation; the first page is the room.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The cover brings the reader to the first page. After that, layout and structure carry the experience.
hint: Think about where the reader's attention goes once the book is open in their hands.

@text
A cover makes a promise. The first page is where that promise is either kept or broken.
Some books never recover from a first page that asks too much.
But even a perfectly designed first page cannot hold a reader if the reading itself costs more than it gives back.

@package
When the Page Gets Heavy
# @true_false, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @reflect, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), true/false intro, teaching: cognitive load

@true_false
A reader who is genuinely interested in a topic will push through a difficult, dense text without tiring.

true: True, interest overcomes difficulty.
consequence: Interest raises the threshold, but it does not remove the limit. Every reader has one.

false: False, even motivated readers slow down and stop when the reading costs too much effort.
consequence: Motivation adds distance, but it does not change the ceiling. Dense writing drains every reader eventually.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Interest adds fuel but does not build structure, so it delays exhaustion without preventing it. The design of the reading itself determines how far the reader gets.
hint: Notice how a genuinely interesting subject can still get abandoned when the writing costs too much.

@text
A professor assigns a 40-page chapter from an academic journal to an undergraduate class.
The chapter covers a topic most students find interesting.
By lecture day, fewer than half have finished.
Most stopped somewhere in the middle, reporting the same thing: they kept rereading the same sentences.
The ideas themselves were not hard, but each sentence carried four or five of them at once, with no room to absorb any before the next arrived.

@text
The same information is later published in a popular science book.
The author breaks the same ideas across shorter sentences, uses section headings, and puts one concept per paragraph.
Students who read the popular book finish it, and several read past the assigned pages.
The information is the same, and the structure is the thing that changed.
One version asked the mind to carry four ideas per sentence, and the other asked it to carry one.

@text
The same pattern appears in government documents.
A legal notice about tax filing, rewritten by a plain-language team, became noticeably faster to read, and far more people who started it actually finished.
Readers had found the original exhausting and gave up long before the form itself got difficult.
The rewrite kept every clause of the law intact.
The only thing it changed was how much the mind had to carry on each line.

@question
In all three cases, what was the shared reason readers stopped?

answer: The content was too advanced for the audience.
consequence: In each case, the audience was capable of understanding the content. The sentences were carrying too much at once.

answer: The writing asked the mind to hold too many ideas at the same time.
consequence: Dense sentences and packed paragraphs force the reader to carry more than the mind can hold while reading forward.

answer: The readers were not motivated enough to finish.
consequence: The students were interested, and the citizens needed to file their taxes. Motivation was not the problem in either case.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Every reader has a cognitive limit, and when the writing crosses it, the reader stops. Structure manages that limit more reliably than motivation does.
hint: Look at what the students and the citizens had in common with each other.

@text
<c:g>Cognitive load</c:g> is the limit the writing either stays below or crosses, and that difference decides whether the reader finishes the page or sets it aside.
It is what sent the students back to rereading the same sentence and pushed the citizens past the point of completing the form.
A UX-friendly book manages cognitive load the way a good path manages a hill: shorter steps, clear markers, and no false summits.
One idea per sentence and one concept per paragraph give the reader a structure they can feel.
The reader's energy then goes into the ideas instead of into untangling the sentence that holds them.

@reflect
A text abandoned from the effort of reading it: a long contract or an academic manual.
A sentence reread because it held too many ideas: a contract clause or a long footnote.
A reading experience that felt effortless despite the complexity: a science book or a how-to guide.

@text
A well-organised book keeps the reader's energy on the ideas rather than on finding the ideas inside the sentences.
But even the cleanest organisation can lose a reader if the book never gives them a reason to keep going.

@package
The Pull of the Unfinished
# @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant C (2 stories), skip intro, teaching: the Zeigarnik effect

@text
A novelist ends her chapter in the middle of a conversation.
The two characters have been arguing for three pages.
The argument has no resolution: the chapter stops at the moment one character is about to speak.
Readers close the book, fully intending to stop for the night.
Most of them find their hand turning the page before the decision to stop has fully registered.

@text
A technical writer structures each section of a software manual so that every concept is fully resolved before the next begins.
Users read one section, put the manual down, and return the next day when they need the next part.
A colleague restructures the same manual, ending each section with an unresolved example, a problem the next section will fix.
Users of the new version read two or three sections at a sitting where they used to read one.
The information was identical, and the incomplete endings changed how the brain treated the pauses.

@question
How did ending sections with an unresolved example affect reading behaviour?

answer: It confused readers, who needed each section resolved before moving on.
consequence: Confusion would have slowed readers down and reduced completion. Session length went up, not down.

answer: It made readers more likely to continue past a natural stopping point.
consequence: An unresolved example creates an open loop, and the brain holds it active until the loop closes.

answer: It had no measurable effect. Readers stopped at the same points as before.
consequence: Both the novelist and the technical writer saw the same result: open endings extended reading sessions.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The mind keeps unresolved problems active. A section that ends before the problem is solved leaves an open loop the reader feels compelled to close.
hint: Notice what happens in the mind when a question is raised but not yet answered.

@text
<c:g>The Zeigarnik effect</c:g> is what kept the chapter break from becoming a rest stop and the section ending from becoming an exit.
The mind holds unfinished tasks more actively than completed ones, and that pull is what moved the readers forward past where they planned to stop.
In a UX-friendly book, the Zeigarnik effect is a structural decision rather than an accident.
Every unresolved question is a thread the brain keeps pulling, and the next chapter is the only place the pulling stops.
A chapter that closes every loop before it ends is a chapter the reader can put down without thinking twice.

@true_false
A reader who feels satisfied at the end of a chapter is more likely to continue reading.

true: True, satisfaction rewards the reader and encourages them to keep going.
consequence: Satisfaction is a good feeling, but a complete feeling. It signals that the session can end.

false: False, a chapter that leaves something unresolved is more likely to keep a reader going.
consequence: Satisfaction closes the loop. An open loop keeps the brain active past the natural stopping point.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Completion settles the mind while incompletion keeps it active. A well-placed open loop does more for reading length than a well-placed reward.
hint: Notice what the brain does with a question whose answer sits on the next page.

@text
A good structure creates enough open loops to keep the reader moving, and closes enough of them to keep the reading from feeling frustrating.
That balance is what separates a book readers describe as compulsive from one they describe as fine.
But even that structure only works if the reader is given the right amount of information at the right moment.

@package
Why Some Books Won't Let Go
# @quote, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant G (2 stories), quote intro, teaching: progressive disclosure

@quote
Perfection is achieved, not when there is nothing more to add, but when there is nothing left to take away.
Antoine de Saint-Exupéry

@text
Suppose a field guide to birds shows exactly one entry per page: a photograph, a name, and one sentence about what makes this bird unusual.
The next entry waits on the next page.
Nothing more is given.
A reader opens the guide to find a sparrow and walks out with the sparrow plus 30 other birds they had not meant to read about.
Readers who open that guide for one bird average 12 minutes inside it before setting it down.

@text
Now suppose a second guide covers the same birds with the same photographs, but each entry adds range maps, breeding data, subspecies notes, migration patterns, and historical sightings.
Everything a serious birder could need is there, all on one page.
Readers who open this guide for one bird find the entry they came for, read it, and close the guide.
Average time: under 3 minutes.
The more complete guide gets less reading time.

@question
Why did the simpler field guide hold readers longer?

answer: The photographs were better quality in the simpler guide.
consequence: Both guides had the same photographs. The difference was in what surrounded them.

answer: The simple guide revealed just enough to make the reader want the next entry.
consequence: One fact, one habit, and one image were enough to close the current question and open the next one.

answer: Readers found the complete guide overwhelming and gave up out of frustration.
consequence: They did not give up. They found what they came for and left, while the simple guide made leaving harder.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Revealing everything at once answers every question in one stop. Revealing just enough turns each stop into a door that opens onto the next one.
hint: Notice what a reader does right after they find the entry they came looking for.

@pause
The eyes of a practiced reader skip more words than they read, and the mind barely notices the difference.

@text
<c:g>Progressive disclosure</c:g> is the practice of revealing information in layers, giving the reader what they need now and holding back what they do not yet need.
It is what made the simpler guide harder to put down than the exhaustive one.
In a UX-friendly book, progressive disclosure shapes the arrangement of detail across the whole reading: the most useful information arrives first, the qualifying detail follows only when the reader is ready for it.
A layer that closes satisfies the reader, and a layer held back at the right moment turns them into a page-turner.
The simple field guide did both on every page.

@true_false
A well-researched book should include all available detail on each topic, so the reader has everything in one place.

true: True, complete information gives the reader the full picture.
consequence: A full picture given all at once is one most readers never finish looking at.

false: False, too much detail too early sends most readers away before the important parts arrive.
consequence: Progressive disclosure keeps the reader at the right depth for each moment. Complete disclosure front-loads the cost.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A reader who gets everything at once finds what they came for and stops. A reader who gets just enough keeps looking for the rest.
hint: Notice what a reader does immediately after finding the answer to their current question.

@text
The design of a UX-friendly book is a set of choices that keep the reader's effort just below their limit and their curiosity just above it.
Visual hierarchy, affordance, cognitive load, open loops, and progressive disclosure are not decorations added after the writing.
Maybe the harder question is which of those five is quietly missing from a book that almost held someone but did not.
